dgeshire, England","Cottenham, South Cambridgeshire District, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"Circa 1505–Circa 1535":"about 1505–about 1535","1526–Male":"1526–Deceased","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1532–1590":"1532–1590","1505–1535":"1505–1535","1535":"1535","1532":"1532","Circa 1535":"about 1535","Circa 1505":"about 1505","1530":"1530","1590":"1590","1505":"1505","1526":"1526","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Cottenham, South Cambridgeshire District, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lane","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in a lane, from Middle English, Old English <i>lane</i>, originally a narrow way between fences or hedges, later used to denote any narrow pathway, including one between houses in a town.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Laighin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Laighean</i>’, a byname meaning ‘spear or javelin’.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Luan</i>’, a byname meaning ‘warrior’, formerly Anglicized as <b>O'Loan</b>. See also   Lamb  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lene","meanings":["Americanized form of Swedish   Lane  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Le(i)ne, most of them a variant of   Lein  .","French (<b>Lène</b>): metonymic occupational name for a shoemaker, from a shortened form of <i>alêne</i> ‘awl’."]},{"name":"Loan","meanings":["English: variant of   Lane  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Luain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Luan</i>’, a name meaning ‘champion, warrior’. In Munster,   Lamb   was commonly adopted as the English equivalent or translation of this name, since another word <i>luan</i> means ‘small lamb’."]},{"name":"Leen","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó Laighin</b>, see   Lane  ."]},{"name":"Looney","meanings":["Irish (Munster): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luanaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Luanach</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>luan</i> ‘warrior’. Compare   Lane   3 and   Lamb   3. Woulfe distinguishes the Munster name <b>Ó Luanaigh</b> from the Ulster name <b>Ó Luinigh</b>, whence   Lunney  . However, many of the Anglicized forms are the same."]},{"name":"Layne","meanings":["English: variant of   Lane  ."]},{"name":"Lones","meanings":["English: variant of   Lane  ."]},{"name":"Lanes","meanings":["English: variant of   Lane  .","French (southern): variant of <b>Lannes</b>, a topographic name from the plural of regional <i>lanne</i> ‘heath, moor’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word."]},{"name":"Lamb","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Lamb</i>, a pet form of   Lambert  .","English: nickname for a meek and inoffensive person, from Middle English <i>lamb</i>, or a metonymic occupational name for a keeper of lambs. See also   Lamm  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luain</b> ‘descendant of the warrior’, formerly Anglicized as <b>O'Loan</b> (see   Lane   3). MacLysaght comments: \"The form <b>Lamb(e)</b>, which results from a more than usually absurd pseudo-translation (<i>uan</i> ‘lamb’), is now much more numerous than <i>O'Loan</i> itself.\"."]},{"name":"Lain","meanings":["English: variant of   Lane  .","Shortened form of Scottish and northern Irish   McLain   (see   McLean  ).","Spanish (<b>Laín</b>): from the personal name <i>Laín</i>, from Latin <i>Flavinus</i>."]},{"name":"Lone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Munir, Naheed, Nasser, Aamer, Jamil, Kashif, Muhammad, Nasir, Riaz, Salim, Samie, Wasim.  German Wolf.  Scandinavian Arlys, Juel, Tor.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads in southwestern Norway, named with Old Norse <i>lón</i> ‘calm, deep pool (in a river)’.","English: variant of   Lane  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Lane was born about 1505, in Cambridgeshire, England. She had at least 3 sons. She died about 1535, in Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"Circa 1505–Circa 1535":"umbes 1505–umbes 1535","1526–Male":"1526–Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1532–1590":"1532–1590","1505–1535":"1505–1535","1535":"1535","1532":"1532","Circa 1535":"umbes 1535","Circa 1505":"umbes 1505","1530":"1530","1590":"1590","1505":"1505","1526":"1526","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Cottenham, South Cambridgeshire District, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"Circa 1505–Circa 1535":"noin 1505–noin 1535","1526–Male":"1526–Kuollut","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1532–1590":"1532–1590","1505–1535":"1505–1535","1535":"1535","1532":"1532","Circa 1535":"noin 1535","Circa 1505":"noin 1505","1530":"1530","1590":"1590","1505":"1505","1526":"1526","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Cottenham, South Cambridgeshire District, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fr":{"Circa 1505–Circa 1535":"environ 1505–environ 1535","1526–Male":"1526–Décédé","1530–Male":"1530–Décédé","1532–1590":"1532–1590","1505–